# What’s the truth?

I've always found comfort in the predictability of code. However, developing Gen AI applications is not like building traditional software applications or predictive models. As I started developing Generative AI applications, I had to continuously remind myself of the non-deterministic nature of these applications. In that sense, GenAI, with its ability to produce diverse and creative outputs, clashes with the deterministic nature of traditional applications. In particular, there seems to be no one answer to the question: what’s the truth?

*How is traditional software engineering and ML different from Gen AI?*  
In traditional software development, we have clear-cut metrics for success. Unit tests pass or fail, models achieve a certain accuracy. One example of a machine learning challenge with a clear-cut metric for success is the Yelp Challenge. The Yelp Challenge is a competition held by Yelp from 2014 to 2016 to improve the accuracy of Yelp's restaurant recommendation system. The goal of the competition was to develop an algorithm that could predict whether or not a user would like a restaurant based on their past reviews. The ground truths were well defined and had low variance. You liked the restaurant or you didn’t. On the other hand, the inputs had high variance as each user had different age, gender, etc.  
![][image1]

With GenAI, variance shifted from inputs to outputs. Imagine prompting an LLM for a "delicious recipe." What's delicious is subjective, varying from person to person. There's no single "right" answer. This lack of a clear ground truth makes evaluation and improvement a unique challenge.  
![][image2]  
This uncertainty has profound implications.   
For businesses, building trust becomes more challenging. How can you guarantee your application works when the output itself is inherently variable? What are the metrics you use to evaluate your application? For developers, the iterative development process, so familiar in software engineering, becomes less straightforward. We're used to relying on testing frameworks, benchmarks and metrics to guide our progress. For GenAI applications, those familiar metrics are still the target, yet less well defined.

So the question becomes: What’s a good way (i.e. a data-driven way) to build trust in GenAI applications from a business perspective enabling continuous deployment to production? It’s an important question and one I’ll get to next time.
